oakcurric:unit-463
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Further study of the four joins"@en ;
  curric:slug "further-study-of-the-four-joins" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils strengthen cursive skills by practising the four joins with
  attention to letter size and orientation. They write sentences in cursive, applying each
  join type, using capital letters and focusing on when to lift the pencil, as well as when
  to use lead-ins and lead-outs."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit strengthens pupils' cursive handwriting skills by building on
  the four joins learned in Year 2. Through focused practice in writing cursive sentences,
  pupils develop greater control and accuracy - mastering pencil lifts, consistent letter size,
  and proper spacing. These skills enable them to produce smoother, more connected writing
  across all curriculum areas, enhancing readability and written expression. The fluency
  developed here prepares pupils for the next unit on letter strings, where they will apply
  their cursive writing skills to words containing prefixes and suffixes.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-463-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-463-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-463-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-463-4 ;
  curric:id "463"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.846333Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-handwriting-fluency .

oakcurric:unit-907
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poetry inspired by big and small objects: understanding form"@en ;
  curric:slug "poetry-inspired-by-big-and-small-objects-understanding-form" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and respond to the classic sonnet, 'Ozymandias' by Percy
  Bysshe Shelley. They will learn to write a variety of different forms of poetry, including
  a haiku, kenning and free verse poem. Finally, they will perform their own free verse
  poems inspired by big and small objects."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on 'The Magic Box': reading imaginative poetry',
  where pupils used Kit Wright's poem 'The Magic Box' as inspiration to write their own
  imaginative poetry. In this unit, pupils will develop their knowledge by exploring a range of
  different poetic forms and structures. They will use some poetic devices to write a free
  verse poem about big and small objects. This unit prepares pupils for writing more of their
  own poetry, using the more abstract topic of weather, in 'Poetry inspired by weather'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-907-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-907-2 ,
