    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-892
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'When the Sky Falls': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "when-the-sky-falls-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the novel, 'When the Sky Falls'. They
  discuss the historical context and explore the main characters and their motives. Finally,
  pupils spot comparisons and connections between the characters and explore the key
  concepts and themes within the text."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of characterisation,
  which was explored in 'A Kind of Spark', where pupils explored a narrative through the lens
  of a neurodiverse individual. In this unit, pupils explore the historical setting of the
  Second World War through the lens of a young boy. They explain character motives and make
  inferences about character emotions based on evidence within the text. This unit prepares
  pupils for 'When the Sky Falls': narrative and journalistic report writing', where they will
  use the book as a stimulus for writing.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-892-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-892-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-892-3 ;
  curric:id "892"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.621056Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-fiction-reading-spine .

oakcurric:unit-98
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Character: big, beautiful and eye words"@en ;
  curric:slug "character-big-beautiful-and-eye-words" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn to grow their descriptive vocabulary in discrete
  lessons for the first time. They learn a range of vocabulary to support writing about
  characters, including ambitious vocabulary for big, beautiful and eye words that can be
  applied to descriptive writing passages."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on previously taught vocabulary in narrative
  writing and reading units throughout KS1, for example in the Year 2 unit ''Lucky Dip':
  narrative writing'. For the first time, pupils learn a range of ambitious vocabulary at
  word-level in discrete lessons, focusing here on building vocabulary to describe characters,
  including big, beautiful and eye words. This unit prepares pupils for learning a wider range
  of vocabulary to describe characters in narrative writing, including small, confident and shy
  words, in the Year 3 unit 'Character: small, confident and shy words'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-98-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-98-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-98-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-98-4 ;
  curric:id "98"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.663710Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-vocabulary-knowledge .

oakcurric:unit-469
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Building fluency with note taking, choice, quotations and emphasis"@en ;
  curric:slug "building-fluency-with-note-taking-choice-quotations-and-emphasis" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils practise note-taking and choose between pen or pencil for
  different tasks. They write famous quotations in cursive and learn different techniques to
  write with emphasis. Pupils also learn which type of handwriting is most appropriate for a
  given task or purpose."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This final step in pupils' handwriting journey fosters an independent
  approach to their learning. Developing pupils' ability to strike the right balance between
  handwriting speed and accuracy equips them with essential note-taking skills. Having built a
  strong foundation in cursive techniques, pupils decide when it is appropriate to add emphasis
  techniques to enhance the quality of their writing and when it is appropriate to write in
  print. These skills prepare pupils for the transition to secondary school, where smooth,
  efficient and adaptable handwriting are essential tools for learning.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-469-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-469-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-469-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-469-4 ;
  curric:id "469"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.694545Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-handwriting-fluency .

oakcurric:unit-913
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poetry about personal experiences"@en ;
  curric:slug "poetry-about-personal-experiences-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read, respond to and perform a variety of poems by different
  poets. They explore many themes, including love, hope, belonging, hate and resilience.
  Finally, pupils write their own poem about a personal experience."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of writing poetry from the
  Y4 unit, 'Poetry inspired by weather'. In this unit, pupils will revisit a range of poetic
  forms and devices and build on their learning by reading, responding to and writing poems
  linked to feelings, relationships and experiences. Through the different poems, pupils will
  explore and discuss some complex themes. This unit prepares pupils for 'Poetry of place',
  where they will build on these experiences, reading and analysing classic and contemporary
  poetry that evokes a strong sense of place, before writing their own.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-913-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-913-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-913-3 ,
