oakcurric:unit-910
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poetry inspired by weather"@en ;
  curric:slug "poetry-inspired-by-weather" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read, respond to and perform four different poems associated
  with weather. They discuss the poetic devices used and explore structure and imagery.
  Finally, they write their own poems inspired by the weather."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on 'John Lyons Poetry', where pupils read and
  responded to a range of poems by John Lyons, exploring form, structure and language, before
  writing poems of their own. In this unit, pupils build on these experiences, reading and
  responding to a range of poems that link to the weather. They explore form, structure and
  language, before generating ideas and writing poems of their own.This unit prepares pupils
  for 'Poetry inspired by animals', where they will build on this knowledge by reading and
  analysing classic and contemporary poetry about animals.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-910-7 ;
  curric:id "910"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.701000Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-581
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'The Man on the Moon': narrative writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-man-on-the-moon-narrative-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils write their own version of the short film 'The Man on the
  Moon'. The unit encourages pupils to build on their understanding of the narrative
  structure of opening, build-up, climax and resolution. Each section is written with a
  focus on using certain sentence types."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of narrative writing skills
  built in the Year 3 unit ''The BFG': reading and narrative writing'. In that unit, pupils
  learnt to write a narrative opening and build-up with increasing levels of sophistication and
  authorial intent; here, pupils write a complete narrative, using the opening, build-up,
  climax, resolution structure, to write their own version of a short film. This is more
  sophisticated than the KS1-level beginning, middle, end structure. This unit prepares pupils
  for the Year 3 unit 'The Iron Man': narrative writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-581-7 ;
  curric:id "581"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.706068Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-655
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Mirror': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "mirror-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the dual narrative text, 'Mirror'. They
  explore the two stories by inferring meaning from images in the text. Finally, pupils make
  connections to and from the text, as well as engaging with key themes."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the prior unit, 'The Unforgotten Coat', where
  pupils discussed how cultural influences affect an individual. In 'Mirror', pupils will
  compare and contrast two families from different countries and cultural backgrounds through
  use of a dual narrative text. Pupils will make connections between the two stories in
  'Mirror', as well as developing the skill of prediction. This unit prepares pupils for the
  future unit, 'Front Desk', where they will explore an individual's experience of moving to a
  new country.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-655-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-655-2 ;
  curric:id "655"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.725786Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community ,
    oakcurric:thread-fiction-reading-spine .

oakcurric:unit-654
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Curious Creatures Glowing in the Dark': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "curious-creatures-glowing-in-the-dark-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the non-fiction text 'Curious Creatures
  Glowing in the Dark'. They will identify the features of a non-fiction text and use
  strategies to retrieve information. Finally, pupils will read the text to learn
  specifically about the anglerfish."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' learning around the features of
  non-fiction texts, which was explored through the non-fiction information text 'Rushing
  Rivers' in Year 3. In this unit, pupils explore more non-fiction, learning about purpose,
  audience and layout. Pupils will develop their retrieval strategies to find information about
  glowing creatures. This unit prepares pupils for the future unit 'Crazy about Cats', where
  they will further discuss the features of non-fiction writing and consider the author's use
  of language to engage the reader.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-654-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-654-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-654-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-654-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-654-5 ;
  curric:id "654"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.771597Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform .

oakcurric:unit-665
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Little Red Riding Hood': journalistic report"@en ;
  curric:slug "little-red-riding-hood-journalistic-report" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils write a journalistic report recounting the events of the
  fairy tale 'Little Red Riding Hood'. Pupils learn to frame a fictional starting point as a
  newsworthy event before writing in paragraphs in the journalistic style, including
  incorporating witness quotes."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding of non-fiction writing
  from the Year 4 unit 'Anglerfish: non-chronological report'. However, the focus here is on
  writing a journalistic report. In this unit, pupils are introduced to journalistic writing
  for the first time. Pupils learn to write in a journalistic tone a recount of a newsworthy
  event from a fictional stimulus, including quotations from bystanders. This unit prepares
  pupils for the Year 5 unit 'The Titanic: journalistic report writing', which is based on a
  true historical event.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-665-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-665-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-665-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-665-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-665-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-665-6 ;
  curric:id "665"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.774172Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform .

oakcurric:unit-649
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Polar regions: essay writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "polar-regions-essay-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about how climate change is affecting the polar
  regions. They organise their knowledge into a clear essay structure with an introduction,
  paragraphs and a conclusion. They then write an essay that outlines how climate change is
  negatively impacting the polar regions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of how to write a clear,
  well-structured essay from the previous Year 6 unit, 'The Empire Windrush: essay writing'.
  The question for this essay requires pupils to write a single line of argument, maintaining
  that rising global temperatures affect the polar regions negatively. Pupils write with
  credibility, using statistics, facts, evidence bases, logic, passive voice, persuasive
  techniques and structure. This unit prepares pupils for further essay writing in the Year 6
  unit, 'Ancient Islamic civilisation: essay writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-649-10 ;
  curric:id "649"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.776602Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-essay-writing .

oakcurric:unit-587
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Shakespeare's 'Romeo and Juliet': diary and narrative writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "shakespeares-romeo-and-juliet-diary-and-narrative-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn to empathise with and understand different characters
  in one of Shakespeare's iconic plays. They write a diary entry from Juliet's perspective,
  a climactic narrative scene based on the duel scene and begin to debate around a key
  question raised from the play."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils' understanding of how Shakespeare develops
  character, a concept introduced in the Year 5 unit, 'Shakespeare's 'Macbeth': narrative and
  soliloquy writing'. Pupils develop empathy skills to write a compelling diary entry from a
  character's perspective, varying tense and language structures to suit its purpose. Climactic
  writing devices are developed to build tension in the writing of a duel scene, including
  short sentence structures, dialogue to move action forward and precise verbs and adverbs.
  This unit prepares pupils for further Shakespeare study at KS3 level.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-587-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-587-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-587-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-587-4 ,
