  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-869
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Swallow's Kiss': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "swallows-kiss-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the text 'Swallow's Kiss'. They learn
  about verse novels as a type of narrative and discuss the key themes in the text. Finally,
  pupils will make connections and recommendations to enhance their reading experiences."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the prior unit, 'Leaf', where pupils explored
  the theme of the environment. In this unit, pupils will develop their understanding of themes
  through engaging with an illustrated verse novel. They will engage with the key themes of
  empathy, hope and community and share take-away ideas and responses. Through rich
  discussions, pupils will explore the characters and make personal connections. This unit
  prepares pupils for 'Poetry about personal experiences', where they will read and respond to
  a range of poems about feelings, emotions and experiences.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-869-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-869-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-869-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-869-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-869-5 ;
  curric:id "869"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.784626Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-95
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Weather: wind and hot words"@en ;
  curric:slug "weather-wind-and-hot-words" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn a wider range of vocabulary to support writing
  descriptively about the weather, including ambitious vocabulary for wind and hot words
  that can be applied to descriptive writing passages."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on previously taught vocabulary for describing
  characters, including clever and clumsy words in the Year 3 unit 'Character: clever and
  clumsy words'. Here, pupils learn new words to support the descriptive writing of the
  weather, specifically for wind and hot scene-setting. This unit prepares pupils for learning
  a wider range of vocabulary to describe settings and scenes in narrative writing, including
  cold, calm and stormy words, in the Year 4 unit 'Weather: cold, calm and stormy words'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-95-7 ;
  curric:id "95"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.787148Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-vocabulary-knowledge .

oakcurric:unit-309
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How Bees Make Honey: explanation text"@en ;
  curric:slug "how-bees-make-honey-explanation-text" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils research how bees make honey in order to write a
  clearly-presented explanation text. Pupils focus on writing facts using subject-specific
  vocabulary within Year 3 level sentence structures. Pupils learn to join two ideas of
  cause and effect across more than one sentence."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of certain non-fiction
  writing conventions from the Year 3 unit 'The Portia Spider: non-chronological report'. Here,
  pupils write their first explanation text in this curriculum, using the paragraphing
  structure of an introduction, themed sections and conclusion. Pupils include a variety of
  formal fronted adverbials and a range of causal conjunctions in their writing. Year 3 level
  sentence structures are reviewed and applied. This unit prepares pupils for more explanation
  text writing in the Year 3 unit, 'Mummification: explanation writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-309-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-309-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-309-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-309-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-309-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-309-6 ;
  curric:id "309"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.875885Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform .

oakcurric:unit-585
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'How to Train Your Dragon': diary and narrative writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "how-to-train-your-dragon-diary-and-narrative-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils use their knowledge of the text 'How To Train Your Dragon' to
  write a setting description, a narrative opening and a diary entry. Pupils use one
  stimulus to write for several outcomes, writing for different purposes by demonstrating
  certain techniques in each."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils' knowledge of a novel from the Year 5 unit 'How
  To Train Your Dragon': reading' as well as diary writing skills in the Year 4 unit 'Into the
  Forest': diary writing'. Pupils use knowledge of the text to create three pieces of writing,
  each using certain devices to meet the text purpose. Examples include precise vocabulary in
  the setting description, a range of sentence structures in the opening and first person and
  tense variation in the diary entry. This unit prepares pupils for more narrative opening
  writing in the Year 5 unit 'The Viewer': narrative writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-585-7 ;
  curric:id "585"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.880853Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-575
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Into the Forest': diary writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "into-the-forest-diary-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils write a diary entry based on the picture book 'Into the
  Forest' by Anthony Browne. Pupils use the book as a starting point from which they write a
  diary entry, focusing on using the first person perspective consistently and practising
  the skill of varying tense accurately."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge of diary writing from the
  Year 3 unit 'The Journey': diary writing'. The unit starts with the analysis of the plot of
  the picture book 'Into the Forest' by Anthony Browne, where pupils discuss key themes
  explored by Browne. Pupils then write their own version of a diary entry from the
  protagonist's perspective in three paragraphs. This unit prepares pupils for writing another
  diary entry in the Year 5 unit ''How To Train Your Dragon': diary and narrative writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-575-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-575-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-575-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-575-4 ;
  curric:id "575"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.883304Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community ,
    oakcurric:thread-traditional-tales .

oakcurric:unit-3765
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poet focus: 'Overheard in a Tower Block' by Jospeh Coelho"@en ;
  curric:slug "poet-focus-overheard-in-a-tower-block-by-jospeh-coelho" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read, explore and peform a selection of poems from Joseph
  Coelho's collection, 'Overheard in a Tower Block'. They are first introduced to the poet,
  before exploring the poems and getting tips from Joseph on how to perform the poems."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """The unit uses and builds on pupils understanding of poetry, performance
  and Joseph Coelho from the unit 'Werewolf Club Rules'. This unit enriches and develops their
  understanding by reading more poems by Coelho, and starting to look at the performance of
  longer and more complex poems. This unit prepares pupils for the unit 'Poetry about personal
  experiences', where they will learn more about performance, and will see how a range of other
  poets approach performances about personal experiences.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3765-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3765-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3765-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3765-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3765-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3765-6 ;
  curric:id "3765"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.906907Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-3684
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Successful speeches"@en ;
  curric:slug "successful-speeches" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils analyse abridged, rewritten versions of famous speeches made
  by Greta Thunberg, Emma Watson and Malala Yousafzai. They learn the techniques that the
  writer of each speech has used to ensure it meets its purpose."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' speaking and listening skills
  developed in the Year 5 unit 'Introduction to debate'. Pupils continue to use their speaking
  and listening skills as well as their reading skills to analyse and understand the power of
  speeches. Notably, pupils analyse abridged, rewritten versions of famous speeches made by
  Greta Thunberg, Emma Watson and Malala Yousafzai, unpicking the techniques that the speech
  writer has used to ensure it meets its purpose. This unit prepares pupils for further
  discussion and oracy work in the Year 6 unit 'Talking Transitions'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3684-8 ;
  curric:id "3684"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.912463Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-spoken-language .

oakcurric:unit-3721
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'The Final Year': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-final-year-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the verse novel, 'The Final Year'. They will
  read and respond to the poems, exploring characterisation and relationships within the
  story. Finally, pupils will identify the key themes and share their personal responses."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the prior unit, 'Wonder: book club', where
  pupils developed their own personal response to a text with themes of bullying and
  acceptance. In this unit, pupils will explore the themes of identity and self-expression
  through an illustrated verse novel. Pupils will explore the protagonist and his emotional
  journey in the story and develop their own take-away ideas. This unit prepares pupils for the
  future unit, 'Cloud Busting: book club', where they will explore different perspectives
  around themes of friendship and bullying, also written in the form of a verse novel.""" ;
  curric:id "3721"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.918203Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-703
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'When the Sky Falls': narrative and journalistic report writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "when-the-sky-falls-narrative-and-diary-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils write a narrative climax and a journalistic report based on
  the text, 'When the Sky Falls', focusing on changing tone and style to meet each outcome's
  purpose. The journalistic report is based on an event in the novel. These outcomes can be
  used for KS2 SATS writing."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the Year 6 unit, 'Climate emergency:
  journalistic report writing', in which pupils got into role as a journalist writing a report
  based on the climate emergency. Here, pupils use a fictional event from the novel 'When the
  Sky Falls' to write a narrative climax and a journalistic report, using climactic narrative
  techniques like short sentences and fast time adverbials in the first and key journalistic
  phraseology and passive voice in the second. This unit's outcomes can be used for pupils' KS2
  writing portfolios as they demonstrate all taught cohesive devices.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
