oakcurric:unit-877
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'A Journey through Greek Myths': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "a-journey-through-greek-myths-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore 'A Journey through Greek Myths'. They will
  develop their understanding of the features of Greek myths and read and discuss three
  different stories. Finally, pupils will compare myths and discuss themes."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge and understanding of myths,
  which were explored in the prior unit 'Marcy and the Riddle of the Sphinx'. In this unit,
  pupils will examine and discuss the features of a traditional myth. They will read and
  explore a range of well-known examples, building their comprehension through rich discussions
  and questioning. This unit prepares pupils for 'Arthur and the Golden Rope', where they will
  extend their understanding of myths by reading and exploring a modern myth.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-877-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-877-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-877-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-877-4 ;
  curric:id "877"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.032493Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-traditional-tales ,
    oakcurric:thread-fiction-reading-spine .

oakcurric:unit-468
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Building handwriting fluency through speed, choices and writing dialogue"@en ;
  curric:slug "building-handwriting-fluency-through-speed-choices-and-writing-dialogue" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils develop their handwriting speed and their ability to select
  the apppropriate writing implement suited to a given task. They practise applying their
  cursive handwriting to writing famous quotations, dialogue, a journalistic report and a
  non-chronological report."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on Year 4 by extending pupils' skills to writing longer
  sections at speed. Learning to reflect on the differences in their handwriting when writing
  quickly versus slowly, promotes ownership and encourages pupils to find a balance between
  precision and speed. They also gain independence by choosing between pen and pencil to match
  the task. Practising longer sections in cursive, helps pupils to embed text conventions from
  the Year 5 curriculum as well as punctuation and grammar rules. This unit prepares pupils for
  the more complex demands of the final handwriting unit in Year 6.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-468-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-468-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-468-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-468-4 ;
  curric:id "468"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.040944Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-handwriting-fluency .

oakcurric:unit-590
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Shakespeare's 'Macbeth': narrative and soliloquy writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "shakespeares-macbeth-narrative-and-soliloquy-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils have their first taste of Shakespearean play scripts. They
  analyse the witches' prologue of this iconic play as a starting point for writing a
  narrative opening. Pupils investigate the central character, writing a soliloquy based on
  Macbeth's famous dagger monologue."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils' understanding of play scripts introduced in
  the Year 3 unit 'Reading and performing scripts'. Pupils experience an authentic
  Shakespearean script for the first time, analysing the witches' prologue and using it as
  inspiration to write a narrative opening that emphasises descriptive vocabulary to capture
  the scene's atmosphere. Pupils write a soliloquy from Macbeth's perspective, using tense
  variation, imagery and rhetorical questions. This unit prepares pupils for the Year 6 unit,
  'Shakespeare's 'Romeo and Juliet': diary and narrative writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-590-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-590-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-590-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-590-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-590-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-590-6 ;
  curric:id "590"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.064190Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-fiction-writing .

oakcurric:unit-87
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Simple, compound and adverbial complex sentences"@en ;
  curric:slug "simple-compound-and-adverbial-complex-sentences" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn two comma rules within different sentence structures:
  compound and adverbial complex sentences. Pupils revise simple, compound and adverbial
  complex sentences and extend their knowledge by learning that an adverbial clause can come
  first or second in a complex sentence."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on learning around writing simple, compound and
  adverbial complex sentence structures learnt in the Year 2 grammar unit 'Adverbial complex
  sentences'. The critical learning in this unit is that there are conventions around when
  commas are placed within compound and adverbial complex sentence structures. Pupils also
  learn for the first time that the adverbial clause can be first or second in a complex
  sentence. This unit prepares pupils to learn a new complex sentence structure in the Year 4
  grammar unit 'Simple, compound, adverbial and relative complex sentences'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-87-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-87-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-87-3 ,
