    oakcurric:priorknowledge-685-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-685-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-685-9 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-685-10 ;
  curric:id "685"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.173824Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform ,
    oakcurric:thread-developing-essay-writing .

oakcurric:unit-819
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Weather: descriptive writing"@en ;
  curric:slug "weather-descriptive-writing" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils practise discrete narrative writing skills, basing their
  writing around typical stormy or desert island weather. Pupils practise using figurative
  language appropriately and with increasing sophistication; they also finish the unit by
  illustrating their descriptive scene writing."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils' knowledge of some key narrative skills, making
  use of high-level vocabulary from the Year 4 units 'Weather: cloudy, dark and rainy words'
  and 'Weather: wind and hot words'. The unit begins with pupils reviewing some figurative
  language, including simile and personification, applying it to writing Year 4 level sentence
  structures with a focus on description to complete two outcomes: a description about a storm
  and a desert island. This unit prepares pupils for using figurative language within narrative
  in the Year 4 unit, 'The Happy Prince': narrative writing'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-819-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-819-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-819-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-819-4 ;
  curric:id "819"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.176106Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 .

oakcurric:unit-3718
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Laura Mucha: performance poetry"@en ;
  curric:slug "laura-mucha-performance-poetry" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read, respond to and perform a variety of poems by the poet,
  Laura Mucha. They will watch Mucha perform her own poems and learn from her about what
  makes an effective performance. Finally, pupils will practise different skills to perform
  each poem effectively to an audience."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' experiences of performing poetry for
  an audience, which were explored in the prior Y2 unit, 'Performance Poetry'. In this unit,
  pupils will continue to develop their performance skills through exploration of the poet,
  Laura Mucha. They will read a number of poems on different themes, each time performing the
  poem and focusing on different performance skills. This unit prepares pupils for 'Poetry
  about personal experiences', where they will read, respond to and write poems linked to
  feelings, relationships and experiences.""" ;
  curric:id "3718"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.249050Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

oakcurric:unit-220
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Simple, compound, adverbial and relative complex sentences"@en ;
  curric:slug "simple-compound-adverbial-and-relative-complex-sentences" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn a new sentence structure: the relative complex
  sentence. In so doing, they learn a new comma rule for how to embed a relative clause
  within a main clause. Pupils revise main and adverbial clauses and phrases as well as
  simple, compound and adverbial complex sentences."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on learning around writing simple, compound and
  adverbial complex sentence structures reviewed in the Year 3 grammar unit 'Simple, compound
  and adverbial complex sentences'. Pupils learn a new set of subordinating conjunctions
  (after, before, while) and practise writing adverbial complex sentences in two formations,
  making use of a comma in one of these. A new sentence structure is taught - the relative
  complex sentence - which has a new comma rule. This unit prepares pupils to learn one more
  complex sentence structure in the Year 5 grammar unit 'Five sentence types'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-220-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-220-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-220-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-220-4 ,
