oakcurric:unit-893
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'When Stars are Scattered': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "when-stars-are-scattered-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the graphic novel memoir, 'When Stars are
  Scattered'. They discuss Omar Mohamed's experience of living in a refugee camp in Kenya
  and identify the key themes in the text. Finally, pupils make personal connections and
  recommendations."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge and understanding of
  graphic novels, which was explored in 'El Deafo: book club'. In this unit, pupils respond to
  a memoir in graphic novel form with increasingly mature themes, exploring the refugee
  experience. Pupils engage with the themes of perserverance and hope and share their own
  unique, take-away ideas from the text. This unit prepares pupils for the future unit, 'No
  Country and Frizzy: graphic novels exploring identity and belonging', where they will explore
  a fictional narrative with some similar themes.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-893-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-893-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-893-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-893-4 ;
  curric:id "893"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.258426Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-308
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Punctuation"@en ;
  curric:slug "punctuation" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils review a range of previously taught punctuation, including
  speech punctuation for three different types of speech sentence and apostrophes for
  contraction and singular and plural possession. They are also introduced to hyphens,
  colons, semi-colons and bullet points."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on punctuation rules of three varied speech
  sentences and how to use apostrophes for contraction, singular and plural possession in the
  Year 5 grammar unit 'Speech punctuation, parenthesis and apostrophes'. New learning includes
  how to use the hyphen, using ellipsis for authorial effect, building text cohesion with
  colons and semi-colons and using bullet points accurately. This unit prepares pupils for
  further English learning at KS3 level by developing their punctuation agility to directly
  apply to all pieces of writing, including creative and analytical pieces.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-308-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-308-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-308-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-308-4 ;
  curric:id "308"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.262066Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-grammatical-knowledge .

oakcurric:unit-868
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'The Sheep Pig': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-sheep-pig-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the classic narrative 'The Sheep Pig'. They
  use retrieval and inference to develop their comprehension of the text. Finally, pupils
  identify the turning point in the story, marking the change in direction of the plot and
  discussing how this affects the story."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on learning around narrative structure and
  inference explored in the prior unit, 'Anansi and the Antelope Baby'. In this unit, pupils
  will read and listen to a more complex narrative and will discuss characterisation in more
  detail. They will explore the structure of the narrative and how turning points in the plot
  affect the story. This unit prepares pupils to develop their inference skills further with a
  more complex narrative and story structure in 'The Borrowers' in Year 4.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-868-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-868-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-868-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-868-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-868-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-868-6 ;
  curric:id "868"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.265733Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-fiction-reading-spine .

oakcurric:unit-1052
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'How To Train Your Dragon': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "how-to-train-your-dragon-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the illustrated chapter book, 'How To Train
  Your Dragon'. They develop their understanding of characterisation and build comprehension
  of the text through rich discussions. Finally, pupils explore the themes of loyalty,
  bravery and what makes a hero."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on the prior unit, 'Arthur and the Golden Rope', where
  pupils explored a modern myth that drew inspiration from Norse culture. In 'How To Train Your
  Dragon', pupils will read and discuss a longer, fictional narrative that draws from Norse
  culture and will discuss another unlikely hero. Pupils will explore common character traits
  of heroes. They will engage in 'Reader's Theatre', reading aloud with expression and
  intonation to bring characters and scenes to life. This unit prepares pupils for the future
  unit, 'Beowulf', where pupils will encounter a hero in an epic poem.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1052-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1052-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1052-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1052-4 ;
  curric:id "1052"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.275789Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-fiction-reading-spine .

oakcurric:unit-878
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'The Wild Robot': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-wild-robot-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the illustrated chapter book, 'The Wild
  Robot'. They will share their opinion on the text and explore the key themes of identity,
  adaptation and technology. Finally, pupils will develop personal responses, as well as
  making connections to other texts."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' discussions around the themes of
  identity and belonging, which were explored in 'The Iron Man'. Pupils will return to these
  themes through exploration of characters and relationships. Pupils will learn the features of
  an illustrated chapter book, as well as building confidence in making connections and
  recommendations to enhance the reading experience. In this unit, pupils discuss the theme of
  nature vs technology, preparing pupils for the future unit, 'Greenling', where they will
  explore the theme of environmentalism through a picturebook text.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-878-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-878-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-878-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-878-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-878-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-878-6 ;
  curric:id "878"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.277451Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-1071
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Danny Chung Does Not Do Maths': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "danny-chung-does-not-do-maths-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the novel, 'Danny Chung Does Not Do Maths'.
  They explore and discuss the story and its key themes of hope, prejudice and creativity.
  Finally, pupils explore the characters and relationships in the text and make personal
  connections and recommendations."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' exploration of the theme of identity,
  which was discussed in prior unit, 'El Deafo'. The protagonist in this text experiences
  similar challenges in relation to their cultural heritage. Pupils will engage in rich
  discussions around the characters, as well as building confidence in making connections and
  recommendations. In this unit, pupils explore traditions and stereotypes of Chinese families.
  It prepares pupils for future unit, 'Frizzy', where they will engage in a graphic novel
  exploring cultural expectations placed on a character of Dominican heritage.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1071-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1071-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1071-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1071-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1071-5 ;
  curric:id "1071"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.298019Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-897
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'The Miraculous Journey of Edward Tulane': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-miraculous-journey-of-edward-tulane-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the illustrated chapter book, 'The
  Miraculous Journey of Edward Tulane'. They share their opinion on the text and explore the
  key themes of love, compassion and loss. Finally, pupils make connections and
  recommendations for two other texts."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the prior unit, 'Varjak Paw', where pupils
  explored an illustrated chapter book. In this unit, pupils will develop their understanding
  of the features of an illustrated chapter book, through exploration of a narrative containing
  themes of love, compassion and loss. Pupils will discuss friendships and relationships
  between the characters. This unit prepares pupils for the future unit, 'The Unforgotten
  Coat', where they will revisit the importance of friendship and love in the context of a
  nomad/refugee's experiences of migrating to England.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-897-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-897-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-897-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-897-4 ;
  curric:id "897"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.299676Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-875
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'El Deafo': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "el-deafo-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the graphic novel memoir 'El Deafo'. They
  share their opinion on the text and explore the key themes of identity, family and
  self-acceptance. Finally, pupils engage in rich discussions around the characters in the
  text."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' experience of texts with connections
  to the real world. In 'Swallow's Kiss', pupils explored a fictionalised narrative about the
  refugee experience; in this unit pupils engage with a graphic novel retelling of author Cece
  Bell's real-life experience of hearing loss. Pupils will continue to develop their
  understanding of characterisation and themes. This unit prepares pupils for 'When Stars are
  Scattered: book club', where they will explore a graphic novel memoir written by a refugee,
  which contains themes of war, politics and disability.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-875-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-875-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-875-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-875-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-875-5 ;
  curric:id "875"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.308865Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform ,
    oakcurric:thread-book-club ,
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community .

oakcurric:unit-871
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Rushing Rivers': reading"@en ;
  curric:slug "rushing-rivers-reading" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils read and explore the non-fiction text 'Rushing Rivers'. They
  identify the features of a non-fiction text and use strategies to retrieve information.
  Finally, pupils summarise their learning on rivers, discussing it with others to help
  consolidate knowledge."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' learning around the features of
  non-fiction texts, which was explored through the non-fiction narrative 'The Pebble in my
  Pocket'. In this unit, pupils explore a non-fiction information text, identifying the
  specific layout features and how to navigate these to retrieve the desired information. This
  unit prepares pupils for future learning in 'Curious Creatures Glowing in the Dark', where
  children will develop their understanding of these features and discuss how they can be used
  to engage the intended audience.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-871-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-871-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-871-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-871-4 ;
  curric:id "871"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.345642Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-reading-and-writing-texts-that-inform .

oakcurric:unit-890
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Girl of Ink and Stars': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "girl-of-ink-and-stars-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the novel, 'Girl of Ink and Stars'. They
  identify the key themes in the text, which is a blended genre of myths and magical
  realism. Finally, pupils discuss the characters in the text, as well as making personal
  connections and recommendations."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge and understanding of myths,
  which was explored in the Y4 unit, 'Arthur and the Golden Rope'. In this unit, pupils will
  explore a novel, which blends the genres of myth and magical realism, and discuss their
  responses to the text. Pupils will discuss and explore the heroic character traits of the
  protagonist, Isabella, and discuss her actions in the story. This unit prepares pupils for
  discussing different interpretations of the texts they read, which is explored further in
  'When Stars are Scattered: book club'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-890-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-890-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-890-3 ;
  curric:id "890"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.565867Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-traditional-tales ,
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-883
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Front Desk': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "front-desk-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore and discuss the fictional novel, 'Front Desk'. They
  share their opinion on the text and explore the key themes of prejudice and
  discrimination. Finally, pupils discuss the characters in the text, as well as making
  personal connections and recommendations."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on the prior unit, 'Mirror', where pupils
  compared and contrasted two families from different countries and cultural backgrounds. In
  'Front Desk', pupils will discuss the experience of moving to a new country and develop their
  personal responses to the text. Pupils will make connections and recommendations, enhancing
  the reading experience and broadening their understanding of literature. This unit prepares
  pupils for 'Front Desk: persuasive letter writing', where they will take inspiration from a
  scene in the text 'Front Desk' to write a persuasive letter.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-883-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-883-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-883-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-883-4 ;
  curric:id "883"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.638452Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-book-club ,
    oakcurric:thread-modern-literature-strand-1-identity-belonging-and-community .

oakcurric:unit-914
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Developing reading preferences in Year 6"@en ;
  curric:slug "developing-reading-preferences-in-year-6" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will develop their reading preferences by exploring text
  adaptations. Pupils will learn about the benefits of engaging with translated texts from
  around the world. Finally, they will develop their awareness of different forms of
  reading, focusing on picture books."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on 'Developing reading preferences in Year 5',
  where pupils developed reading for pleasure through exploration of a range of text types. In
  this unit, pupils will build on this knowledge through the introduction to a range of texts
  suitable for Year 6. They will learn the importance of reading books written by a range of
  authors/illustrators to learn about different cultures and perspectives. This unit prepares
  pupils for 'No Country and Frizzy: graphic novels', where they will explore a specific text
  type in more detail.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-914-8 ;
  curric:id "914"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.646454Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-developing-reading-preferences .

oakcurric:unit-867
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "'Marcy and the Riddle of the Sphinx': book club"@en ;
  curric:slug "marcy-and-the-riddle-of-the-sphinx-book-club" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils discuss and explore the story 'Marcy and the Riddle of the
  Sphinx'. They will develop their understanding of the features of a modern myth. Finally,
  pupils will explore the key themes in the text and develop a personal response."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' knowledge and understanding of a
  quest narrative, which was explored in the prior unit 'The Moon Dragons'. In this unit,
  pupils will read another quest narrative interwoven with themes of mythology. Pupils will
  identify and explore the key themes within the text and develop their confidence in sharing
  their interpretations and opinions through dicussions with others. This unit prepares pupils
  for further exploration of modern myths in the future unit 'Arthur and the Golden Rope',
  where pupils will draw comparisons between texts.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-867-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-867-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-867-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-867-4 ;
  curric:id "867"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.680159Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-traditional-tales ,
    oakcurric:thread-book-club .

oakcurric:unit-3769
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Poetry by Valerie Bloom"@en ;
  curric:slug "poetry-by-valerie-bloom" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils study the poetry of Valerie Bloom. They will read a selection
  of Valerie's poetry, practise responding to it, and they will listen to her reading her
  poetry too."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit uses and builds on pupils' understanding and appreciation of
  poetry from previous units, including 'Poetry about personal experiences'. In this unit,
  pupils look in detail at just one poet, and think about they have developed their responses
  to personal experiences over multiple poems. The unit prepares pupils for their future poetry
  units, including 'The Final Year', where they will look at a cohesive collection of poetry.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3769-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3769-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3769-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3769-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3769-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3769-6 ;
  curric:id "3769"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.836822Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-english-key-stage-2 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-appreciation-of-poetry .

